<node id="Market Selloff">
  <data key="d0">Market Selloff</data>
  <data key="d1">event</data>
  <data key="d2">A Market Selloff is defined as a notable, substantial, or significant decrease in the overall value of stocks within a market, often characterized as a sharp downturn. This phenomenon is primarily driven by investor concerns, leading to a widespread downward trend in stock prices across various sectors.

The primary factors contributing to investor apprehension during a market selloff include prevailing or rising interest rates and governmental or industry regulations, often coupled with regulatory uncertainty. Investors react collectively to these concerns, anticipating potential negative impacts on corporate earnings, broader economic growth, or their investment returns. Consequently, this anticipation prompts investors to sell off their holdings, which in turn fuels the decline in stock values across the market.&lt;SEP&gt;Market selloff refers to the significant decline in stock values due to investor concerns over interest rates and regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;A market selloff is a significant decline in stock values due to investor concerns over interest rates and regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;A significant decline in stock values, attributed to investor concerns over interest rates and regulatory uncertainty.&lt;SEP&gt;A market selloff is a significant decline in stock values, attributed to investor concerns over rising interest rates and regulatory uncertainty.&lt;SEP&gt;Market selloff refers to the significant decline in stock values due to investor concerns over interest rates and regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;A market selloff refers to the significant decline in stock values due to investor concerns over interest rates and regulations.</data>
