<node id="Max Bill">
  <data key="d0">Max Bill</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Swiss architect, designer, painter, sculptor, and graphic artist. He inherited the ideology of Bauhaus and laid the foundation for modern design. He served as the first rector of the Ulm School of Design and designed the Ulm Stool. (1908-1994)&lt;SEP&gt;A Swiss architect, artist, and designer who inherited the Bauhaus ideology, conceived the Ulm Stool, and served as the first rector of the Ulm School of Design. He was born in 1908 and died in 1994, laying the foundation for modern design across various fields from spoons to urban planning.&lt;SEP&gt;Max Bill was a designer born in 1908 and died in 1994, known for his extensive design activities and considered the last master of Bauhaus. He was also the first rector of Ulm School of Design.&lt;SEP&gt;A figure who laid the foundation of modern design, covering various fields. He was active as a painter, sculptor, and graphic artist, contributed to the succession of Bauhaus ideology, co-designed the Ulm Stool, and was the first rector of the Ulm School of Design.&lt;SEP&gt;Max Bill is a designer, painter, sculptor, and graphic artist who co-designed the Ulm Stool in 1954 with Hans Gugelot. He was the first rector of the Ulm School of Design and is known for laying the foundation of modern design, covering diverse fields from spoons to urban planning. He was dedicated to inheriting the Bauhaus ideology, which sought to fuse artistry and the functionality of mass production.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f484700b8f584c97b2a965ce95f5d752&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8c6a355152f3149b1a67320fd1f08a52&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f37adcf76bfa0b63b612de2654ab7ac6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3586dcab6b282878bcaf595ac6fd2245&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2db7e0c2a92a184a27e188bc4286ed70</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1772697075</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ulm Stool">
  <data key="d0">Ulm Stool</data>
  <data key="d1">product</data>
  <data key="d2">The Ulm Stool is an artisan product made from 5 parts using woodworking techniques without nails. It weighs approximately 2.1kg and measures W39x H44xD29cm. Its original model is characterized by a design using lightweight spruce wood for portability and a charm of changing color over time. It is priced at 49,500 yen and sold by Metrokus.&lt;SEP&gt;A multi-functional stool designed by Max Bill and Hans Gugelot. It can be used as a chair, side table, shelf, footrest, or ottoman. It is assembled using woodworking techniques with 5 parts without nails. It weighs approximately 2.1kg, with dimensions W39x H44xD29cm, and costs 49,500 yen.&lt;SEP&gt;A multifunctional stool conceived by Max Bill and Hans Gugelot in 1954. It can be used as a chair, side table, shelf, footrest, or ottoman. It is assembled using five parts with wood joinery techniques without nails. It weighs approximately 2.1kg, measures W39x H44xD29cm, and costs 49,500 yen.&lt;SEP&gt;The Ulm Stool is a multifunctional stool designed in 1954, considered a "masterpiece stool" for its versatility. It is made without nails using a woodworking technique of fitting 5 parts and originally uses lightweight spruce wood. Its dimensions are W39x H44xD29cm, weighing approximately 2.1kg, and priced at 49,500 yen.&lt;SEP&gt;A masterpiece stool designed by Max Bill and Hans Gugelot. It is versatile, transforming into a chair, side table, shelf, footrest, or ottoman. It is assembled from 5 parts using wood joinery without nails, weighs about 2.1kg, measures W39xH44xD29cm, and is sold for 49,500 yen.&lt;SEP&gt;The Ulm Stool is a multi-functional stool designed in 1954 by Max Bill and Hans Gugelot. It can be used as a chair, side table, shelf, footrest, and ottoman, and is considered a "masterpiece stool." It is made without nails using 5 parts and joinery, weighs approximately 2.1kg, and measures W39xH44xD29cm. The original version was made from lightweight spruce wood and changes color over time. It embodies the philosophy of Max Bill and is currently sold by Metrocs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f484700b8f584c97b2a965ce95f5d752&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e3b5730698c6919a72fa8fe9e365553a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8c6a355152f3149b1a67320fd1f08a52&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f37adcf76bfa0b63b612de2654ab7ac6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3586dcab6b282878bcaf595ac6fd2245&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2db7e0c2a92a184a27e188bc4286ed70</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1772697075</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bauhaus">
  <data key="d0">Bauhaus</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A design ideology that pursued the fusion of artistry and the functionality of mass production. Max Bill inherited this ideology, and the Ulm School of Design propagated it.&lt;SEP&gt;A design ideology that sought to integrate artistry with the functionality of mass production. Max Bill inherited this ideology and applied it to the Ulm School of Design.&lt;SEP&gt;Bauhaus is an ideology that advocates for the functional fusion of artistry and mass production.&lt;SEP&gt;A design ideology that sought to fuse artistry with the functionality of mass production. Max Bill contributed to its succession, and the Ulm School of Design propagated its principles.&lt;SEP&gt;Bauhaus is an ideology that advocates for the fusion of artistry and the functionality of mass production. Its principles were inherited and propagated by figures like Max Bill and institutions like the Ulm School of Design.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f484700b8f584c97b2a965ce95f5d752&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8c6a355152f3149b1a67320fd1f08a52&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f37adcf76bfa0b63b612de2654ab7ac6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3586dcab6b282878bcaf595ac6fd2245&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2db7e0c2a92a184a27e188bc4286ed70</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1772697075</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ulm School of Design">
  <data key="d0">Ulm School of Design</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">A design school established in Ulm, West Germany in 1954. It propagated the Bauhaus ideology, and Max Bill served as its first rector.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f484700b8f584c97b2a965ce95f5d752</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1772687491</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hans Gugelot">
  <data key="d0">Hans Gugelot</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Max Bill's assistant and a person who participated in the design of the Ulm Stool.&lt;SEP&gt;Max Bill's assistant who participated in the design of the Ulm Stool.&lt;SEP&gt;Hans Gugelot was an assistant to Max Bill and co-designed the Ulm Stool in 1954.&lt;SEP&gt;Max Bill's assistant who participated in the design of the Ulm Stool.&lt;SEP&gt;Hans Gugelot is a designer who co-designed the Ulm Stool in 1954 with Max Bill.</data>
