<edge source="Market Selloff" target="Regulatory Uncertainty">
  <data key="d7">24.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relation "(Market Selloff, Regulatory Uncertainty)" describes a causal connection where regulatory uncertainty is identified as a significant factor contributing to a market selloff. This attribution is consistently made by financial analysts and reflects prevailing investor sentiment.

Specifically, regulatory uncertainty is understood to be a primary cause of heightened investor concerns. These elevated concerns among investors are then widely attributed as the direct reason for a subsequent market selloff. Therefore, the relationship illustrates how a lack of clarity or predictability in regulatory environments can trigger investor apprehension, ultimately leading to a downturn in overall market performance.&lt;SEP&gt;Investor concerns over regulatory uncertainty are attributed as a cause for the market selloff.&lt;SEP&gt;Analysts attribute the market selloff to investor concerns over regulatory uncertainty.&lt;SEP&gt;Investor concerns over regulatory uncertainty are attributed as a cause for the market selloff.&lt;SEP&gt;Investor concerns over regulatory uncertainty are attributed as a cause for the market selloff.</data>
  <data key="d9">attributed to,attribution,causal factor,causation,cause,caused by,economic factor,investor concern,market factor</data>
