<edge source="Supply Constraints" target="Crude Oil">
  <data key="d7">39.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relation between Crude Oil and Supply Constraints describes a direct influence where limitations in the supply of crude oil significantly support and drive its market price upward. This relationship highlights a fundamental economic principle: when the availability of a commodity like crude oil is restricted or limited, its market value tends to increase, especially in the face of consistent or rising demand.

Specifically, supply constraints are identified as a significant factor that supports crude oil prices. This means that any condition leading to a reduction in the crude oil supply acts as an upward pressure on its price.&lt;SEP&gt;Crude oil prices were supported by supply constraints.&lt;SEP&gt;Crude oil prices were supported by supply constraints.</data>
  <data key="d9">causal factor,causation,cause,contributing factor,factor,impact,market driver,market factor,market influence,market support,price driver,price influence,price rally,price support,support,supported by</data>
